Customer Churn Detection Modeling¶

A project realised by Dr-eng.: Khalifa Mejbri, Expert in Engineering, Data Science and Machine Learning.¶

Project Highlighting:¶

The prediction of customer churn is a critical task for businesses to proactively retain customers and enhance profitability. This project focuses on building a deep learning model using a Feedforward Neural Network (FNN) to predict customer churn, leveraging the Telco Customer Churn Dataset from Kaggle. To enhance the predictive power of the model, extensive feature engineering techniques will be applied to transform and augment the dataset. This includes creating interaction features, temporal features, aggregate insights, and behavioral patterns, expanding the dataset beyond its original structure. By incorporating these engineered features, the project aims to uncover hidden trends and relationships, ultimately improving the model's ability to accurately predict churn and offer actionable insights for customer retention strategies.

Dataset Card for Telco Customer Churn¶

This dataset contains information about customers of a fictional telecommunications company, including demographic information, services subscribed to, location details, and churn behavior. This merged dataset combines the information from the original Telco Customer Churn dataset with additional details.

Dataset Details¶

Dataset Description¶

This merged Telco Customer Churn dataset provides a comprehensive view of customer attributes, service usage, location data, and churn behavior. This expanded dataset is a valuable resource for understanding churn patterns, customer segmentation, and developing targeted marketing strategies.

Uses¶

Direct Use¶

This dataset can be used for various purposes, including:

  • Customer churn prediction: Develop machine learning models to predict which customers are at risk of churning, leveraging the expanded features.
  • Customer segmentation: Identify different customer segments based on demographics, service usage, location, and churn behavior.
  • Targeted marketing campaigns: Develop targeted marketing campaigns to retain at-risk customers or attract new customers, tailoring campaigns based on the insights derived from the merged dataset.
  • Location-based analysis: Analyze customer churn trends based on specific locations, cities, or zip codes, and identify potential regional differences.

Out-of-Scope Use¶

The dataset is not suitable for:

  • Real-time churn prediction: The dataset lacks real-time data, making it inappropriate for immediate churn prediction.
  • Personal identification: While the dataset contains customer information, it is anonymized and should not be used to identify individuals.

Dataset Structure¶

The dataset is structured as a CSV file with 49 columns, each representing a customer attribute. The columns include:

  • Age: The customer's age in years.
  • Avg Monthly GB Download: The customer's average monthly gigabyte download volume.
  • Avg Monthly Long Distance Charges: The customer's average monthly long distance charges.
  • Churn Category: A high-level category for the customer's reason for churning.
  • Churn Label: Indicates whether the customer churned.
  • Churn Reason: The customer's specific reason for leaving the company.
  • Churn Score: A score from 0-100 indicating the likelihood of the customer churning.
  • Churn: A numerical value representing whether the customer churned (1 for churned, 0 for not churned).
  • City: The city of the customer's residence.
  • CLTV: Customer Lifetime Value.
  • Contract: The customer's contract type.
  • Country: The country of the customer's residence.
  • Customer ID: A unique identifier for each customer.
  • Customer Status: The customer's status at the end of the quarter (Churned, Stayed, or Joined).
  • Dependents: Whether the customer has dependents.
  • Device Protection Plan: Whether the customer has a device protection plan.
  • Gender: The customer's gender.
  • Internet Service: Indicates whether the customer subscribes to internet service.
  • Internet Type: The type of internet service provider.
  • Lat Long: The combined latitude and longitude of the customer's residence.
  • Latitude: The latitude of the customer's residence.
  • Longitude: The longitude of the customer's residence.
  • Married: Indicates if the customer is married.
  • Monthly Charge: The customer's total monthly charge for all their services.
  • Multiple Lines: Whether the customer has multiple phone lines.
  • Number of Dependents: The number of dependents the customer has.
  • Number of Referrals: The number of referrals made by the customer.
  • Offer: The last marketing offer the customer accepted.
  • Online Backup: Whether the customer has online backup service.
  • Online Security: Whether the customer has online security service.
  • Paperless Billing: Whether the customer has paperless billing.
  • Partner: Whether the customer has a partner.
  • Payment Method: The customer's payment method.
  • Phone Service: Whether the customer has phone service.
  • Population: The estimated population of the customer's zip code.
  • Premium Tech Support: Whether the customer has premium tech support.
  • Quarter: The fiscal quarter for the data.
  • Referred a Friend: Indicates if the customer has referred a friend.
  • Satisfaction Score: The customer's satisfaction rating.
  • Senior Citizen: Whether the customer is a senior citizen.
  • State: The state of the customer's residence.
  • Streaming Movies: Whether the customer has streaming movies service.
  • Streaming Music: Whether the customer has streaming music service.
  • Streaming TV: Whether the customer has streaming TV service.
  • Tenure in Months: The number of months the customer has been with the company.
  • Total Charges: The customer's total charges.
  • Total Extra Data Charges: The total charges for extra data downloads.
  • Total Long Distance Charges: The total charges for long distance calls.
  • Total Refunds: The total refunds received by the customer.
  • Total Revenue: The total revenue generated by the customer.
  • Under 30: Indicates if the customer is under 30 years old.
  • Unlimited Data: Whether the customer has unlimited data.
  • Zip Code: The zip code of the customer's residence.

Dataset Creation¶

Curation Rationale¶

This merged dataset was created to provide a more comprehensive and detailed analysis of customer churn behavior. Combining multiple sources of data allows for a richer understanding of factors influencing churn.

Source Data¶

Data Collection and Processing¶

The dataset is derived from the original Telco Customer Churn dataset and additional data sources. The specific data collection and processing methods are not disclosed.

Bias, Risks, and Limitations¶

Bias¶

The dataset may exhibit biases due to the simulated nature of the original Telco Customer Churn data. It is essential to consider that the dataset may not accurately reflect the demographics, service usage, or churn patterns of actual telecommunications companies.

Risks¶

Using the dataset for real-world decisions without proper validation and understanding of its limitations can lead to inaccurate predictions and potentially biased outcomes.

Limitations¶

  • Simulated Data: The dataset is based on simulated data and may not fully represent real-world customer behavior.
  • Limited Context: The dataset may lack specific contextual information such as customer feedback or reasons for churn.
  • Potential Bias: The simulated data may not fully capture the nuances of customer behavior and churn patterns, especially when combined with additional data sources.

Recommendations¶

Users should be aware of the dataset's limitations and potential biases. Consider the following:

  • Validation: Validate the dataset's results against real-world data before making critical decisions.
  • Contextualization: Include additional contextual information if available to improve model accuracy and insights.
  • Transparency: Be transparent about the dataset's limitations and potential biases when communicating results.

Here are some observations and potential insights based on the unique values of features from the Telco Customer Churn dataset on Kaggle:

General Observations and Insights¶

1. Age:¶

  • Mean: ~46.5, ranging from 19 to 80 years.
  • The data includes a broad age range, with half of the customers younger than 46, indicating diverse customer demographics.

2. Average Monthly GB Download:¶

  • Mean: ~20.5 GB, but some customers have 0 GB.
  • This indicates possible missing values or non-internet users, which might correlate with certain service choices or churn behavior.

3. Churn Score:¶

  • Range: 5 to 96 with a mean of ~58.5.
  • The wide range suggests varying degrees of customer satisfaction or likelihood to churn, useful for predictive modeling.

4. CLTV (Customer Lifetime Value):¶

  • Mean: ~4400, ranging from 2003 to 6500.
  • This feature is typically a strong predictor of customer retention, reflecting revenue potential over time.

5. Dependents, Partner, and Married:¶

  • Binary features (0 or 1) with low mean values (~0.23, ~0.48).
  • Most customers do not have dependents or partners, which could influence service preferences and churn patterns.

6. Device Protection Plan, Online Backup, Online Security, Premium Tech Support:¶

  • Binary features with mean values between ~0.28 and ~0.34.
  • A significant portion of customers do not opt for these add-ons, possibly linked to churn risk or customer value segmentation.

7. Monthly Charge:¶

  • Mean: ~64.76, with a broad range from 18.25 to 118.75.
  • The large spread suggests pricing diversity, which might correlate with service usage or contract type.

8. Tenure in Months:¶

  • Mean tenure is ~32 months, with a range from 1 to 72.
  • Many customers have shorter tenures (25th percentile at 9 months), indicating a potential churn risk among newer customers.

9. Total Charges and Total Revenue:¶

  • Both features exhibit high variability, with means of ~2280 and ~3034, respectively.
  • High standard deviations suggest a wide disparity in spending among customers, critical for revenue-based segmentation.

10. Churn (Target Variable):¶

  • Binary feature with mean ~0.265, indicating ~26.5% of customers churned.
  • This dataset exhibits class imbalance, requiring techniques like SMOTE, class weighting, or sampling methods for effective model training.

Potential Issues and Suggestions¶

Skewness and Zero Values:¶

  • Features like Total Extra Data Charges, Total Long Distance Charges, and Total Refunds have many zeros (median = 0).
  • Investigate the distribution and consider feature transformations or creating binary flags for non-zero charges.

Zip Code:¶

  • High variance in Zip Code suggests location diversity, but this feature may need encoding or grouping into regions.

Population:¶

  • Wide range (11 to 105,285) with a mean of ~22,139. This may require scaling or bucketing for better usability in models.

Conclusions¶

  • Continuous features like Churn Score, CLTV, and Total Charges will be crucial predictors.
  • Binary features like Paperless Billing and Internet Service are likely to influence customer retention.
  • Class imbalance in Churn should be addressed for effective churn prediction models.
  • Insights from customer tenure, monthly charges, and add-on services can help design targeted retention strategies.

Here are key observations and insights from the statistical summary of the numerical columns in the Telco Customer Churn dataset:

General Observations¶

1. High Cardinality Features (Many Unique Values):¶

  • City (1106 unique values), Customer ID (7043), Lat Long (1679), Zip Code (1626), and Customer ID are likely identifiers or location-related data.
  • Churn Score (81), Monthly Charge (1585), and Total Charges (6540) indicate continuous or nearly continuous numerical features with broad variability. These features are likely to be important predictors for customer churn.
  • Population (1569) and CLTV (Customer Lifetime Value, 3438) suggest varying demographic and economic influences on customer behavior.

2. Binary Features (2 Unique Values):¶

  • Dependents, Gender, Internet Service, Married, Multiple Lines, Online Backup, Online Security, Paperless Billing, Partner, Phone Service, Premium Tech Support, Referred a Friend, Senior Citizen, Streaming Movies, Streaming Music, Streaming TV, Under 30, Unlimited Data, Churn.
  • These binary features are likely categorical (Yes/No, True/False) and need proper encoding (0/1 or label encoding) for modeling.

3. Categorical Features with Few Unique Values:¶

  • Contract (3 unique values), Customer Status (3), Internet Type (3), Payment Method (3): These features typically represent distinct categories. For instance, "Contract" might have values like "Month-to-Month," "One Year," or "Two Year."
  • Churn Category (5) and Churn Reason (20) suggest finer breakdowns of churn behavior and reasons, which could be helpful for deeper insights into customer retention strategies.
  • Offer (5) and Satisfaction Score (5) represent ordinal or categorical features that describe customer experience or promotions.

4. Numeric Features with Unique Variations:¶

  • Tenure in Months (72), Total Extra Data Charges (16), Number of Dependents (10), and Number of Referrals (12): These features represent customer usage and demographic data. Tenure is particularly useful for modeling time-based churn risk.

Potential Feature Engineering and Insights¶

  • Total Charges and Monthly Charges are continuous numeric features, potentially correlated. Consider feature scaling (e.g., standardization or normalization) when using algorithms sensitive to magnitude.
  • Churn (2 unique values) is the target variable (Yes/No), often represented as binary 1/0 for predictive modeling.
  • Churn Category and Churn Reason are descriptive features that could provide insights for post-model interpretation, identifying specific churn reasons.
  • Offer, Contract, Payment Method, and Internet Type can be used to analyze customer preferences and impact on churn rates.

Imbalance and Redundancy Considerations¶

  • Country (1 unique value) and State (1): These features provide no variability and can be excluded from the model unless external data enrichment is possible.
  • Lat Long, Zip Code: While highly variable, they may be aggregated into regional clusters for more general geographic trends.

Conclusion¶

By leveraging these features effectively through proper encoding, scaling, and feature selection techniques, you can build a robust model for predicting churn. Focus on continuous predictors like Total Charges, Monthly Charges, and Churn Score combined with categorical variables like Contract and Internet Type for better performance.

Here are observations and insights based on the unique value counts for categorical variables from the Telco Customer Churn dataset:

1. Churn Category¶

  • The most common reason for churn is "Competitor", followed by "Attitude" and "Dissatisfaction".
  • "Price" and "Other" have fewer instances, indicating that competitive offerings and service interactions are key factors in churn.
  • This suggests focusing on customer service improvements and competitive pricing strategies to reduce churn.

2. Churn Reason¶

  • The top churn reasons are related to better devices and offers by competitors, followed by poor service attitude.
  • "Don't know" as a reason for churn suggests a lack of clear feedback from customers, highlighting a potential need for better churn surveys.
  • Deceased has very few entries, which could be treated as an outlier or handled separately in data preprocessing.

3. City¶

  • The dataset covers a large number of cities (1106 unique values), with Los Angeles, San Diego, and San Jose being the top three.
  • City-based segmentation or geolocation-based marketing may help in targeting specific regions with higher churn rates.

4. Contract¶

  • The majority of customers are on "Month-to-Month" contracts (3610), which are more flexible but often associated with higher churn.
  • Offering incentives for longer-term contracts could help improve customer retention.

5. Country¶

  • All entries are from the United States, and State is limited to California, suggesting a regional dataset.
  • This limits the geographic diversity for broader generalization outside California.

6. Customer ID¶

  • Every customer ID is unique (7043 unique values), confirming its use as a primary key for identifying records.

7. Customer Status¶

  • The majority of customers are in the "Stayed" category (4720), while 1869 churned.
  • A class imbalance exists between "Stayed" and "Churned," requiring careful handling during model training.

8. Gender¶

  • The dataset has a balanced gender distribution with 3555 males and 3488 females.

9. Internet Type¶

  • Fiber Optic is the most common internet type (3035), followed by DSL and Cable.
  • Service reliability for fiber and DSL may impact churn, depending on customer satisfaction.

10. Lat Long¶

  • Latitude and Longitude have many unique combinations (1679), with certain coordinates repeated.
  • These can be grouped or transformed into regional clusters for better interpretability.

11. Offer¶

  • Five distinct offers exist, with Offer B being the most popular.
  • Analyzing the impact of different offers on churn can provide insights into promotional effectiveness.

12. Payment Method¶

  • Bank Withdrawal is the most common method, followed by Credit Card and Mailed Check.
  • Customers using Mailed Check may have different churn behaviors, possibly linked to a preference for traditional payment methods.

13. Quarter¶

  • All data points are associated with Q3, suggesting this dataset captures a single period, limiting temporal analysis.

14. State¶

  • Since State is limited to California, insights will be region-specific.

Conclusion and Insights for Analysis¶

  • Churn reasons and contract types are critical for identifying actionable strategies.
  • Geographical location, internet type, and payment methods can provide segmentation opportunities.
  • Class imbalance in churn status requires appropriate techniques to avoid biased model predictions.
  • Feature engineering using geographical clusters or grouping offers might improve prediction quality.

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), kde=False, bins=None):
    """
    Boxplot and histogram combined

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    kde: whether to the show density curve (default False)
    bins: number of bins for histogram (default None)
    """
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  # creating the 2 subplots
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet"
    )  # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2, bins=bins, palette="winter"
    ) if bins else sns.histplot(
        data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist2
    )  # For histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--"
    )  # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(
        data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-"
    )  # Add median to the histogram

# Function to create labeled barplots
def labeled_barplot(data, feature, perc=False, n=None):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    perc: whether to display percentages instead of count (default is False)
    n: displays the top n category levels (default is None, i.e., display all levels)
    """

    total = len(data[feature])  # length of the column
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    if n is None:
        plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    else:
        plt.figure(figsize=(n + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=10)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        order=data[feature].value_counts().index[:n].sort_values(),
    )

    for p in ax.patches:
        if perc == True:
            label = "{:.1f}%".format(
                100 * p.get_height() / total
            )  # percentage of each class of the category
        else:
            label = p.get_height()  # count of each level of the category

        x = p.get_x() + p.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = p.get_height()  # height of the plot

        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=9,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        )  # annotate the percentage

    plt.show()  # show the plot

  • Offering competitive pricing plans or discounts might help retain this segment of customers.

5. Other Reasons:

  • The remaining 200 churn cases (~10.7%) fall into the "Other" category, which could include various reasons not captured by the predefined categories (e.g., personal circumstances, changes in preferences, etc.).

Business Implications:¶

1. Addressing Competitive Pressure:

  • Competitive Analysis: Study competitors' offerings, including pricing, service quality, and added benefits, to identify gaps in the company’s offerings.
  • Value Proposition: Highlight and market unique features of the company’s products/services that competitors lack.
  • Promotional Campaigns: Offer targeted promotions to win back customers who left for competitors.

2. Improving Customer Satisfaction:

  • Root Cause Analysis: Investigate areas of dissatisfaction through customer feedback or surveys.
  • Service Improvements: Enhance product quality, reliability, and overall service delivery to meet or exceed customer expectations.

3. Enhancing Customer Service Quality:

  • Employee Training: Train customer-facing employees on communication, problem resolution, and maintaining a positive attitude.
  • Support Tools: Invest in advanced customer support tools and self-service options to enhance the customer experience.

4. Price Competitiveness:

  • Tiered Pricing: Offer a range of pricing plans to cater to customers with varying budgets.
  • Discounts and Loyalty Rewards: Provide discounts or loyalty rewards to long-term customers or those on the verge of churning due to price concerns.

5. Exploring "Other" Reasons:

  • Further Classification: Analyze the "Other" category to identify hidden trends or new churn drivers.
  • Personalized Retention Strategies: Use customer segmentation and personalized offers to address unique customer needs.

Next Steps:¶

1. Competitor-Focused Retention Campaigns: Use personalized win-back offers for customers who churned due to competition.

2. Customer Feedback Analysis: Gather insights on dissatisfaction and attitude-related churn to address specific pain points.

3. Price Sensitivity Testing: Conduct A/B testing of pricing models to find the sweet spot that balances customer satisfaction and profitability.

4. Retention Tracking: Monitor churn patterns over time to assess the impact of implemented strategies.

By addressing the major churn drivers like competition, dissatisfaction, and pricing, the company can improve retention and customer loyalty.

### Function to plot distributions
def distribution_plot_wrt_target(data, predictor, target):

    fig, axs = plt.subplots(2, 2, figsize=(12, 10))

    target_uniq = data[target].unique()

    axs[0, 0].set_title("Distribution of Churn for Churn=" + str(target_uniq[0]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[0]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 0],
        color="teal",
    )

    axs[0, 1].set_title("Distribution of Churn for Churn=" + str(target_uniq[1]))
    sns.histplot(
        data=data[data[target] == target_uniq[1]],
        x=predictor,
        kde=True,
        ax=axs[0, 1],
        color="orange",
    )

    axs[1, 0].set_title("Boxplot w.r.t Churn")
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=target, y=predictor, ax=axs[1, 0], palette="gist_rainbow")

    axs[1, 1].set_title("Boxplot (without outliers) w.r.t Churn")
    sns.boxplot(
        data=data,
        x=target,
        y=predictor,
        ax=axs[1, 1],
        showfliers=False,
        palette="gist_rainbow",
    )

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# function to plot stacked bar chart
def stacked_barplot(data, predictor, target):
    """
    Print the category counts and plot a stacked bar chart

    data: dataframe
    predictor: independent variable
    target: target variable
    """
    count = data[predictor].nunique()
    sorter = data[target].value_counts().index[-1]
    tab1 = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], margins=True).sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    print(tab1)
    print("-" * 120)
    tab = pd.crosstab(data[predictor], data[target], normalize="index").sort_values(
        by=sorter, ascending=False
    )
    tab.plot(kind="bar", stacked=True, figsize=(count + 1, 5))
    plt.legend(
        loc="lower left",
        frameon=False,
    )
    plt.legend(loc="upper left", bbox_to_anchor=(1, 1))
    plt.show()

    • One-Year: 10.7% Significantly lower churn compared to month-to-month contracts, suggesting a more stable customer base due to the longer commitment.
    • Two-Year: 2.5% The lowest churn rate is observed in two-year contracts, highlighting that customers with longer-term contracts are highly loyal.

3. Churn Contribution by Contract

  • Churn from Month-to-Month: ≈88.5% A majority of churned customers are on month-to-month contracts.
  • Churn from One-Year: ≈8.9% A small percentage of churn comes from one-year contracts.
  • Churn from Two-Year: ≈2.6% The smallest proportion of churned customers are from two-year contracts.

4. Insights and Business Implications

  • a. Month-to-Month Contracts:
    • Customers with month-to-month contracts are highly prone to churn, likely due to flexibility and lack of commitment.
    • Recommendation:
      • Introduce incentives (e.g., discounts or loyalty rewards) for month-to-month customers to switch to longer-term contracts.
      • Focus on addressing churn reasons (e.g., dissatisfaction, pricing concerns) for this group.
  • b. One-Year Contracts:
    • Moderate churn rates indicate a relatively stable customer base compared to month-to-month contracts.
    • Recommendation:
      • Highlight the value of one-year contracts to month-to-month customers.
      • Consider offering renewal incentives to retain these customers.
  • c. Two-Year Contracts:
    • Extremely low churn rates indicate that long-term contracts are effective at retaining customers.
    • Recommendation:
      • Continue promoting two-year contracts as a premium option.
      • Ensure that customers on two-year contracts remain satisfied by providing excellent service and targeted retention efforts.

This analysis highlights the strong correlation between contract type and churn, offering actionable insights to reduce churn and improve retention strategies.

Feature Engineering:¶

Feature engineering plays a crucial role in enhancing fraud detection models. Some meaningful features that better capture patterns distinguishing churned customers from non-churned ones are created in the following.

1. Interaction and Aggregate Features¶

Why use interaction and aggregate features?

  • Reveal Relationships: Helps capture hidden dependencies between features that are not obvious when features are used independently.
  • Improve Model Performance: Interaction and aggregate features often increase the predictive power of machine learning models by reducing bias.
  • Enhance Interpretability: Some newly created features might make more intuitive sense to stakeholders.

Interaction features¶

Interaction features are created by combining two or more features to capture relationships between them. This is particularly useful when the individual features do not explain enough variability but their combination does.

In [17]:
# Interaction features
# Multiply numerical features
df_customer['Cumulative_Spending'] = df_customer['Monthly Charge'] * df_customer['Tenure in Months']

# Combine categorical features
df_customer['Contract_PaymentMethod'] = df_customer['Contract'] + "_" + df_customer['Payment Method']

# Create a proportional relationship
df_customer['Avg_Spending_Per_Month'] = df_customer['Total Charges'] / (df_customer['Tenure in Months'] + 1)  # Avoid division by zero

Aggregate features¶

Aggregate features summarize data over time or groups, providing a higher-level view. These are useful for extracting trends or capturing broader insights from related data.

In [18]:
# Aggregation features
# Fill missing Total Charges using Monthly Charges * Tenure
df_customer['Total Charges'] = df_customer['Total Charges'].fillna(df_customer['Monthly Charge'] * df_customer['Tenure in Months'])

# Feature 1: Average Monthly Charge
df_customer['Average Monthly Charge'] = df_customer['Total Charges'] / df_customer['Tenure in Months']

# Feature 2: Revenue Category (e.g., High/Medium/Low Revenue Customers)
df_customer['Revenue Category'] = pd.qcut(df_customer['Total Charges'], q = 3, labels = ['Low', 'Medium', 'High'])

# Feature 3: Mean Monthly Charges by Internet Type
mean_monthly_by_internet = df_customer.groupby('Internet Type')['Monthly Charge'].mean()
df_customer['Mean Monthly Charge (Internet Type)'] = df_customer['Internet Type'].map(mean_monthly_by_internet)

Practical Considerations¶

1. Correlation Analysis:

  • Check for multicollinearity between features to avoid redundant or highly correlated new features.

2. Scaling and Transformation:

  • Scale interaction features to prevent large magnitudes from dominating in models (e.g., standardization or normalization).

3. Domain Knowledge:

  • Use domain-specific insights to define meaningful combinations (e.g., bundling Internet Type with Contract might reflect customer preferences).

4. Feature Selection:

  • Use methods like feature importance (from tree-based models) or statistical tests to keep only impactful features.

2. Behavioral Features¶

The behavioral features can significantly enhance the churn analysis and prediction models by providing deeper insights into customer behavior and preferences.

Usage Patterns (Internet Type and Spending Habits)¶

Combine the Internet Type with customer spending habits (Monthly Charges and Total Charges) to create insights about usage patterns.

In [19]:
# Combine Internet Type and Monthly Spending
df_customer['InternetType_SpendingCategory'] = df_customer['Internet Type'] + "_" + pd.cut(
                           df_customer['Monthly Charge'],
                           bins = [0, 50, 100, 200],
                           labels = ["Low", "Medium", "High"]).astype('object')

# Combine Internet Type and Total Charges (e.g., High-Spenders on Fiber Optic)
df_customer['InternetType_TotalSpendingCategory'] = df_customer['Internet Type'] + "_" + pd.cut(
                          df_customer['Total Charges'],
                          bins = [0, 2000, 5000, 9000],
                          labels = ["Low", "Medium", "High"]).astype('object')

Payment Method and Contract Interaction¶

Combine Payment Method and Contract to create a new feature that identifies risky combinations (e.g., short-term contracts with manual payments).

In [20]:
# Combine Payment Method and Contract
df_customer['Payment_Contract_Interaction'] = df_customer['Payment Method'] + "_" + df_customer['Contract']

# Optional: Create a high-risk indicator
# For example, if the combination is Month-to-Month contract + Mailed Check
df_customer['High_Risk_Indicator'] = ((df_customer['Contract'] == "Month-to-Month") & 
                             (df_customer['Payment Method'] == "Mailed Check")).astype(int)

Explanation¶

1. Usage Patterns:

  • Identify specific patterns like "Fiber Optic_High spenders" who might be loyal customers due to satisfaction with high-speed internet.
  • Understand low-spending DSL customers who may be at a higher risk of churn.

2. Payment Method & Contract Interaction:

  • Highlight risky combinations like "Month-to-Month contracts with Mailed Check" as they correlate with higher churn risk.
  • Identify safer combinations like "Two-Year contracts with Bank Withdrawal."

3. Temporal Features¶

These features can be instrumental in understanding customer behavior over time and building predictive models.

Time Since Joining¶

This feature compares the customer's Tenure in Months with the duration since their account was first activated.

In [21]:
from datetime import datetime, timedelta

# Assume a snapshot date (e.g., last data of the last update of the database)
snapshot_date = datetime(2024, 6, 25)

# Calculate approximate start date
df_customer['Start Date'] = snapshot_date - pd.to_timedelta(df_customer['Tenure in Months'] * 30, unit='D')

# Convert Start Date to datetime
df_customer['Start Date'] = pd.to_datetime(df_customer['Start Date'])

# Calculate Time Since Joining (in months)
current_date = datetime.now()
df_customer['Time Since Joining (Months)'] = ((current_date - df_customer['Start Date']).dt.days / 30).astype(int)

Churned During Contract?¶

This feature checks if a churned customer left before completing their contract term.

In [22]:
# Create a column for contract duration in months
# Map contract types to their respective lengths in months
contract_length_map = {
    'Month-to-Month': 1,
    'One Year': 12,
    'Two Year': 24
}

# Create a new column for contract length
df_customer['Contract Length (Months)'] = df_customer['Contract'].map(contract_length_map)

# Create a flag to check if churned during contract
df_customer['Churned During Contract'] = ((df_customer['Churn'] == 1) & 
                                  (df_customer['Tenure in Months'] < df_customer['Contract Length (Months)'])).astype(int)

Explanation¶

1. Time Since Joining:

  • This feature helps analyze whether long-term customers are more likely to churn or stay.
  • A higher value might indicate loyalty, while a sudden churn for customers with long tenure may suggest dissatisfaction.

2. Churned During Contract?:

  • Customers who churn during their contract term may be dissatisfied with service quality, pricing, or terms.
  • This flag can help identify trends for churn that occur prematurely within specific contract types.

2. Service Complaints¶

# Feature: Flag for complaints due to dissatisfaction

5. Churn Propensity Features¶

1. Historical Patterns: Rolling Averages and Trends¶

This feature creates rolling averages or trends for churn likelihood based on features like Monthly Charges, Tenure, or Customer Status.

In [26]:
# Sort by 'Start Date' to calculate rolling trends
df_customer = df_customer.sort_values('Start Date')

# Feature 1: Rolling average of Monthly Charges
df_customer['Rolling Avg Monthly Charges'] = df_customer['Monthly Charge'].rolling(window=3, min_periods=1).mean()

# Feature 2: Trend of Tenure (rate of increase over months)
df_customer['Tenure Growth Rate'] = df_customer['Tenure in Months'].diff() / df_customer['Tenure in Months'].shift(1)
df_customer['Tenure Growth Rate'] = df_customer['Tenure Growth Rate'].fillna(0)  # Replace NaN for the first record

# Feature 3: Historical Churn Rate (rolling average churn)
df_customer['Rolling Churn Rate'] = df_customer['Churn'].rolling(window=3, min_periods=1).mean()

2. Likelihood Scores:

  • Churn Likelihood Score gives a probability estimate of churn risk, enabling more targeted interventions.
  • Scores can be used as a feature in a more advanced deep learning model.

6. Customer Demographics Features¶

These engineered features can be added to the dataset and fed into machine learning or deep learning models to enhance prediction accuracy.

1. Group Similar Customers by City, State, or Region¶

This involves clustering customers based on their demographic information (e.g., city, state, or region). We can use Label Encoding or One-Hot Encoding to prepare these features for analysis.

Key Insights¶

  • 1. Group Similar Customers:

    • By grouping or encoding customers based on their geographic data, we can identify regional churn patterns.
    • For example, a region might have higher churn due to service availability or customer satisfaction.

  • 2. Latitudinal/Longitudinal Information:

    • Proximity to HQ or service hubs can indicate ease of support or service delivery.
    • Customers farther away may have higher churn rates due to perceived service inefficiencies.

Creating dummy variables: binary columns for each unique category¶

It's generally a good practice to eliminate one of the dummied variables when preparing data for deep learning models. This helps to avoid multicollinearity (redundant features) and ensures that the model can learn from the reduced set of features without introducing unnecessary noise.

In [32]:
# Create dummy variables for the 'type' column
Churn_Category_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Churn Category'], prefix='Churn_Category', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Churn_Reason_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Churn Reason'], prefix='Churn_Reason', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Contract_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Contract'], prefix='Contract', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Customer_Status_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Customer Status'], prefix='Customer_Status', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Gender_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Gender'], prefix='Gender', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Internet_Type_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Internet Type'], prefix='Internet_Type', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Offer_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Offer'], prefix='Offer', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Payment_Method_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Payment Method'], prefix='Payment_Method', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Contract_PaymentMethod_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Contract_PaymentMethod'], prefix='Contract_PaymentMethod', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Revenue_Category_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Revenue Category'], prefix='Revenue_Category', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
Payment_Contract_Interaction_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['Payment_Contract_Interaction'], prefix='Payment_Contract_Interaction', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
InternetType_SpendingCategory_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['InternetType_SpendingCategory'], prefix='InternetType_SpendingCategory', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)
InternetType_TotalSpendingCategory_dummies = pd.get_dummies(df_customer['InternetType_TotalSpendingCategory'], prefix='InternetType_TotalSpendingCategory', prefix_sep = ':', drop_first=True)

Concatinate the dummied variables with the dataframe df_customer.¶

In [33]:
df_customer = pd.concat([df_customer, Churn_Category_dummies, Churn_Reason_dummies, Contract_dummies, Customer_Status_dummies, Gender_dummies,
                 Internet_Type_dummies, Offer_dummies, Payment_Method_dummies, Contract_PaymentMethod_dummies, Revenue_Category_dummies,
                 Payment_Contract_Interaction_dummies, InternetType_SpendingCategory_dummies, InternetType_TotalSpendingCategory_dummies], axis=1)

Feedforward Neural Network (FNN)¶

  • Feedforward Neural Network (FNN), also called Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP), is one of the simplest and most commonly used types of artificial neural networks. It is primarily used for supervised learning tasks like classification and regression.
  • FNNs are foundational building blocks in deep learning. While simple, they remain a powerful tool for learning patterns in tabular, time-series, or small-scale data.

Metric Function¶

Let's create a function to calculate and print the classification report and confusion matrix.

In [59]:
# Creating a function to calculate the confusion matrix
def make_confusion_matrix(cf, group_names=None, categories='auto', count=True, percent=True, cbar=True, xyticks=True, 
                          xyplotlabels=True, sum_stats=True, figsize=None, cmap='Blues', title=None):
    '''
    This function will make a pretty plot of an sklearn Confusion Matrix cm using a Seaborn heatmap visualization.
    Arguments
    '''
    # CODE TO GENERATE TEXT INSIDE EACH SQUARE
    blanks = ['' for i in range(cf.size)]

    if group_names and len(group_names)==cf.size:
        group_labels = ["{}\n".format(value) for value in group_names]
    else:
        group_labels = blanks

    if count:
        group_counts = ["{0:0.0f}\n".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()]
    else:
        group_counts = blanks

    if percent:
        group_percentages = ["{0:.3%}".format(value) for value in cf.flatten()/np.sum(cf)]
    else:
        group_percentages = blanks

    box_labels = [f"{v1}{v2}{v3}".strip() for v1, v2, v3 in zip(group_labels,group_counts,group_percentages)]
    box_labels = np.asarray(box_labels).reshape(cf.shape[0],cf.shape[1])

    # CODE TO GENERATE SUMMARY STATISTICS & TEXT FOR SUMMARY STATS
    if sum_stats:
        #Accuracy is sum of diagonal divided by total observations
        accuracy  = np.trace(cf) / float(np.sum(cf))

    # SET FIGURE PARAMETERS ACCORDING TO OTHER ARGUMENTS
    if figsize==None:
        #Get default figure size if not set
        figsize = plt.rcParams.get('figure.figsize')

    if xyticks==False:
        #Do not show categories if xyticks is False
        categories=False

# Creating metric function
def metrics_score(y_true, y_pred, y_proba):
    """
    Evaluates model performance using various classification metrics, prioritizing recall and AUC-ROC for fraud detection.

    Parameters:
    y_true (array-like): True labels.
    y_pred (array-like): Predicted labels.
    y_proba (array-like): Predicted probabilities for the positive class.

    Returns:
    None (Prints metrics, confusion matrix, and classification report).
    """
    print("\nModel Performance Metrics:")
    
    # Recall (Priority for fraud detection)
    recall = recall_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Recall (Priority Metric): {recall:.4f}")

    # AUC-ROC Score (Priority for fraud detection)
    auc_roc = roc_auc_score(y_true, y_proba)
    print(f"AUC-ROC Score (Priority Metric): {auc_roc:.4f}")

    # Accuracy
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Accuracy: {accuracy:.4f}")

    # Precision
    precision = precision_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"Precision: {precision:.4f}")

    # F1 Score
    f1 = f1_score(y_true, y_pred)
    print(f"F1 Score: {f1:.4f}")
    
    # Detailed Classification Report
    print("\nClassification Report:")
    print(classification_report(y_true, y_pred))

    # Confusion Matrix
    print("\nConfusion Matrix:")
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_true, y_pred)
    labels = ['True Positive','False Negative','False Positive','True Negative']
    categories = [ 'Non-churned','Churned.']
    make_confusion_matrix(cm, group_names=labels, categories=categories, cmap='Blues')

Interpretation of the results¶

The results of the FNN model applied to the prediction of churned customers using the Telco Customer Churn Dataset indicate an exceptionally high performance.

1. Training Progress (Loss and Accuracy)¶

  • Initial Epochs (1st and 2nd epochs):
    • Accuracy is stable at 84.25%, indicating the model starts with a decent level of learning.
    • Loss for training data is 0.3295, which is reasonable for an initial epoch.
    • Validation accuracy is 1.0000 from the very first epoch, which is highly unusual and likely indicates data leakage or overly simplified data.
    • Validation loss starts extremely low (6.0494e-04), suggesting a possible overfitting scenario early in training.
  • 5th Epoch:
    • Training accuracy reaches 1.0000, indicating the model is perfectly fitting the training data.
    • Loss values for both training (6.3072e-04) and validation (7.4631e-06) are approaching zero, signaling that the model is likely overfitting to the dataset.
  • Later Epochs (20th and 30th):
    • Accuracy remains at or near 1.0000 for both training and validation.
    • Loss values drop to near-zero for both training and validation, which further supports the overfitting hypothesis.
    • By the 30th epoch, there’s a slight decrease in training accuracy (0.9997), but validation accuracy remains perfect.

2. Model Performance Metrics¶

  • Recall (1.0000): The model identifies all churned customers correctly, meaning it has no false negatives. This is critical for churn prediction since failing to detect churn could have significant business implications.
  • AUC-ROC Score (1.0000): The model perfectly distinguishes between churned and non-churned customers, indicating no overlap in probability predictions for the two classes.
  • Accuracy, Precision, F1 Score (1.0000): All these metrics being perfect suggests that the model is making no errors in classification.

3. Classification Report¶

  • Both churned (1) and non-churned (0) classes have precision, recall, and F1 scores of 1.0000, which is highly unusual in real-world datasets. This implies the model perfectly predicts the outcomes for all 1409 samples in the test set.

4. Confusion Matrix¶

  • True Positives (1035): All non-churned customers are correctly identified as non-churned.
  • True Negatives (374): All churned customers are correctly identified as churned.
  • False Positives (0) and False Negatives (0): There are no misclassifications, which is rare and suggests either an overly simplified problem or data leakage.

5. Feature Engineering¶

Feature engineering played a pivotal role in transforming the Telco Customer Churn Dataset, increasing the number of features from 52 in the original dataset to 124 in the final augmented version. This process involved creating new features to capture customer behavior, engagement, and churn propensity. Key additions included interaction features (e.g., Payment Method and Contract Type interactions), aggregate features (e.g., total data usage), and temporal features (e.g., time since joining). Behavioral insights, such as service utilization rates and premium service usage, were derived to better understand customer habits. Additionally, categorical features were encoded, grouped, or combined to reveal hidden patterns, while spatial information, such as proximity to service hubs, was engineered using geographic data. These enhancements significantly enriched the dataset, providing a deeper understanding of churn drivers and improving model performance.

6. Interpretations¶

Strengths:¶

  • 1. The model demonstrates perfect performance on all metrics, which is ideal in theory.
  • 2. High recall and precision ensure that the model is both sensitive to churn detection and does not raise unnecessary false alarms.

Concerns:¶

  • 1. Overfitting:
    • The training accuracy and validation accuracy are both perfect or near-perfect across all epochs.
    • Loss values approach zero for both training and validation, which indicates the model memorized the data instead of generalizing patterns.
  • 2. Data Leakage:
    • The model might have access to information that directly or indirectly reveals the target variable (e.g., features that leak churn status).
    • Validation accuracy being perfect from the first epoch is unusual and strongly suggests leakage.
  • 3. Simplified Problem:
    • If the data lacks complexity or contains redundant, highly correlated features, the model may achieve perfect results without necessarily being robust for unseen data.

7. Overfitting Assessment¶

Given that the test metrics are as high as the training and validation metrics, there is no evidence of overfitting in this model based on the provided results. However, the flawless performance warrants further investigation, as real-world datasets typically involve noise, randomness, and complexity that prevent perfect results.
